However, though the idea that noise is a random variable may be a construction that is useful for modelling and it may be justified in analysis of broader themes of microstructure and levels of market efficiency, this exogenous construct may be an over-simplification that is inapprpropriate when looking for more understanding of speculation itself.  Institutional and psychological explanations for noise-trading frequently suggest that there are endogenous non-random elements.

The institutional explanations are assciated with the allocation of credit for investment and trading purposes:  as asset values decline exchanges, banks and other providers of liqudiity require larger margins and deeper haircuts; investors liquidate their fund holdings; the atttraction of hedging increases.  See \citet{BrunnermeierLiquidity} and \citet{Gorton} for an overview of the institutional literature.  Psychological explanations revolve around the common panic, the group-thining and the tendency to read private information from the actions of other investors: the so-called \emph{wisdom of crowds} depends on independent evaluation but as Keynes noted in his discussion of the \emph{beauty contest}, it is generally more important to identify what other investors will believe than acertain underlying, fundamental value \citet[p.101]{Keynes1936}
 
it has also been suggested that speculative technieques can change overtime.  For example, \citet{ShillerFashion} discusses the use of fashionable techniques or fads in investment.  In this way, speculation noise is associated with sentiment and measures of sentiment are then used as ways of measuring speculation. 
