\subsection{Empirical work}
Empirical assessment of speuclation has been limited by the scarcity of data.  It is not very easy to distinguish between speculators and other types of investors.  It is even harder to distinguish those that may be noise-traders from those assumed to be informed.  One approach has been to assume that noise-traders utilise simple investment strategies and to use tests of these strategies as a means of testing speculation.  For example speculation can be identified with momentum trading. It is also possible to assume that certain investors, such as investment banksa and hedge funds, are informed while other trade without inforation. The latter group may include day-traders or private individuals.  

